## F2 — LOW/MEDIUM (Leg 3 design decision) — `SignalADX` ingests overnight gaps and never resets; lone exception to the repo's session-isolation convention

`trend.py:33` documents "ADX is a multi-session trend indicator and intentionally
does not reset at session boundaries," and `adx` uses ungrouped `high.diff()`,
`low.shift(1)`, `close.shift(1)`. So at every session's first RTH bar the True
Range and directional movement include the overnight gap, and the Wilder
recursion carries cross-session memory into the in-session signal zone
(~14–28-bar memory overlaps the bar-20+ signal window).

This is the ONLY TR-style calculation in the repo that ingests overnight gaps.
By contrast:
- `session_atr` (volatility.py:39) computes prior-close via
  `close.groupby(session).shift(1)` — session-isolated.
- `BarGapFromPrevious` (bars.py:116) shifts grouped by session, so the overnight
  boundary is deliberately NOT flagged as a gap.

So the "intentional" comment is real, but (a) it doesn't acknowledge that ADX is
the lone exception to an otherwise consistent session-isolation convention, (b)
it doesn't address that the per-session-open overnight-gap TR/DM spike distorts
the early-to-mid session where signals actually fire, and (c) no test pins the
intended cross-session behavior (Leg 2 — the "intentional" claim is unenforced;
the only ADX test is single-session). The README research question
("Does broader trend strength relate to fade outcomes?") arguably supports a
multi-session ADX, which is why this is a decision to make explicit rather than a
clear bug.

Recommendation: make an explicit, documented decision. Either (a) session-reset
ADX for consistency with session_atr, or (b) keep it cross-session but document
WHY overnight-gap-contaminated TR is acceptable for this one research column and
add a test that asserts the chosen behavior. Right now the behavior is asserted
nowhere.

